<td style="text-align:center"><a href="/wiki/File:Bluetank.png" class="image"><img alt="Portal icon" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Bluetank.png/32px-Bluetank.png" width="32" height="19" class="noviewer" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Bluetank.png/48px-Bluetank.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Bluetank.png/64px-Bluetank.png 2x" data-file-width="400" data-file-height="237" /></a></td>
<td style="padding:0 0.2em;vertical-align:middle;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold"><a href="/wiki/Portal:War" title="Portal:War">War portal</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
<ul>
<li>In 2005, Patton's wife's "Button Box" manuscript was finally released by his family, with the posthumous release of Ruth Ellen Patton Totten's book, <i>The Button Box: A Daughter's Loving Memoir of Mrs. George S. Patton.</i><span class="citation news">Taylor, John M.; Taylor, Priscilla S. (July 23, 2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.washtimes.com/books/20050723-092118-1294r.htm">"Gen. Patton's wife, a New York citizen"</a>. <i>The Washington Times</i>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APatton+%28film%29&amp;rft.atitle=Gen.+Patton%27s+wife%2C+a+New+York+citizen&amp;rft.aufirst=John+M.&amp;rft.aulast=Taylor&amp;rft.au=Taylor%2C+John+M.&amp;rft.au=Taylor%2C+Priscilla+S.&amp;rft.date=July+23%2C+2005&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.washtimes.com%2Fbooks%2F20050723-092118-1294r.htm&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Washington+Times&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li><span class="citation book">Suid, Lawrence H. (2002). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://books.google.com/books?id=zB8J2ho-0k8C&amp;pg=PA260"><i>Guts &amp; Glory: The Making of the American Military Image in Film</i></a>. University Press of Kentucky. pp.&#160;260â278. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780813190181" title="Special:BookSources/9780813190181">9780813190181</a>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APatton+%28film%29&amp;rft.aufirst=Lawrence+H.&amp;rft.aulast=Suid&amp;rft.au=Suid%2C+Lawrence+H.&amp;rft.btitle=Guts+%26+Glory%3A+The+Making+of+the+American+Military+Image+in+Film&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DzB8J2ho-0k8C%26pg%3DPA260&amp;rft.isbn=9780813190181&amp;rft.pages=260-278&amp;rft.pub=University+Press+of+Kentucky&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span> Suid's book contains an extended discussion of the production of <i>Patton</i> and of public and critical response to the film; the discussion occupies most of the chapter, "13. John Wayne, <i>The Green Berets</i>, and Other Heroes".</li>
</ul>
